WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.120
Hello everybody and welcome to this introduction to photon counting CT.

00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:08.800
The way I'm going to frame this talk is by comparing photon counting CT detectors to

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:13.620
conventional computer tomography detectors that we're using in most CT scanners today.

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:18.519
And I want to do this because I feel like photon counting CTs has the potential at least

00:00:18.519 --> 00:00:22.400
to be a stepwise progression in computer tomography technology.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:26.260
There are fundamental differences between these two types of detectors.

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:29.980
So let's look at the diagrams that I've created for the two detectors.

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:34.219
This is the conventional detector we're going to look at and this is the photon counting detector.

00:00:34.219 --> 00:00:39.759
You can see they differ structurally and they're going to differ in their mechanism for detecting X-rays.

00:00:39.759 --> 00:00:44.380
I want to start this talk by looking at an analogy to show you or to highlight the differences

00:00:44.380 --> 00:00:46.879
between the types of detectors.

00:00:46.879 --> 00:00:50.960
If we think of the detectors as being buckets of water, they have some water in them.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:56.500
I've got the conventional detector on the left that's got a finite bucket that doesn't leak water.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:00:58.219
All the water stays in the bucket.

00:00:58.259 --> 00:01:02.780
And the photon counting detector on the right that maintains a constant level of water.

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:08.739
And every time new water is added, that water is going to leak out and the level is going to remain the same.

00:01:08.739 --> 00:01:12.299
Now what we're going to do is fill these buckets with X-rays.

00:01:12.299 --> 00:01:14.739
We're going to fill them with raindrops in this analogy.

00:01:14.739 --> 00:01:20.200
And we're going to plot the changes in water within the buckets over time.

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:24.039
I want you to think of the conventional detectors as being like a scale.

00:01:24.039 --> 00:01:28.060
It's weighing the amount of water that is going into the bucket.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:32.100
And think of photon counting detectors as a water level measure.

00:01:32.100 --> 00:01:37.939
We've got a little gauge on the side of this bucket and we're going to measure the changes in water here.

00:01:37.939 --> 00:01:40.020
Let's look at the conventional detector.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:45.620
Water or X-rays are going to reach the detector over a certain period of time.

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:50.020
A conventional detector is then going to say, what was the weight change in the bucket?

00:01:50.020 --> 00:01:51.960
We're using it like a scale.

00:01:51.960 --> 00:01:53.980
And say how much water was added to that bucket.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:57.420
And we can take the integral of the graph that we generated here.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:02.579
The area under this curve is going to equal the amount of water that has reached the bucket.

00:02:02.579 --> 00:02:04.799
That's what conventional CTs do.

00:02:04.799 --> 00:02:09.840
They measure the total incident X-ray energy over a set period of time.

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:15.420
And we set that by setting the number of projections that we want to take when we're rotating around the patient.

00:02:15.420 --> 00:02:18.500
There's a time interval when we're collecting data.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.719
It's not looking at individual raindrops.

00:02:20.719 --> 00:02:25.740
It's looking at the total number, total amount of raindrops that have reached the detector

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:27.939
or the bucket in this example.

00:02:27.939 --> 00:02:30.180
Photon counting detectors are different.

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:37.740
When the water in this example reaches the bucket, it's going to send out a ripple that is proportional to the size of the raindrop.

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:44.340
And the size of the different raindrops are, in this analogy, represent the different energies of the X-ray photons reaching the detectors.

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:47.100
So watch what happens here and see how it differs.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:50.020
As the raindrops reach the buckets, they send out a ripple.

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:55.180
And the water level measure on the side here is going to measure the size of that ripple.

00:02:55.219 --> 00:02:58.300
Notice how different the graph is here.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:02.180
We're able to count the number of water droplets that have hit the bucket.

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:07.340
And we're able to see the size of the water droplet or the energy of the X-ray photon.

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:13.500
Photon counting detectors have the ability not only to count the number of photons that have reached the detector,

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:18.939
but also to separate those photons into the energy of the X-ray photon.

00:03:18.939 --> 00:03:23.700
You can see here that as we are calculating the area under each one of these curves,

00:03:23.739 --> 00:03:29.339
the area under the curve represents the X-ray photon energy for an individual photon.

00:03:29.339 --> 00:03:33.939
And each blip on this graph represents a separate X-ray.

00:03:33.939 --> 00:03:37.019
You can see how we're able to separate the X-rays out here,

00:03:37.019 --> 00:03:42.659
whereas in conventional detectors, we're just getting the total X-rays over a set period of time.

00:03:42.659 --> 00:03:45.219
We can't say anything about the individual energies.

00:03:45.219 --> 00:03:48.459
And this is the key difference between the two types of detectors.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:54.620
So let's look at conventional CT detectors and see how they differ from photon counting detectors.

00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:58.980
Now in conventional detectors, we use what's known as indirect detection.

00:03:58.980 --> 00:04:03.860
X-ray photons, electromagnetic radiation, is converted into light photons,

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:08.140
the same type of electromagnetic radiation, but now they've got longer wavelengths.

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:12.219
Those light photons are then measured by what's known as a photodiode,

00:04:12.219 --> 00:04:16.579
and that light energy is converted into an electrical current that's stored.

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:17.819
So let's look at the components here.

00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:20.459
First, we've got what's known as the scintillator layer.

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:25.699
We've got, it's usually made of something like gadolinium oxy-sulfite or cesium iodide.

00:04:25.699 --> 00:04:31.740
And what that does, what that's responsible for, is converting X-rays into visible light.

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:36.060
Surrounding the scintillator layer is what's known as the reflective scepter.

00:04:36.060 --> 00:04:41.579
We've got these scepter between each one of the detectors that prevent the light that's generated

00:04:41.579 --> 00:04:43.819
from spreading out to adjacent detectors.

00:04:43.819 --> 00:04:46.459
It keeps it on one single detector.

00:04:46.459 --> 00:04:51.739
And you'll see one X-ray photon makes hundreds, thousands of light photons.

00:04:51.739 --> 00:04:55.019
And those light photons spread out in 360 degrees.

00:04:55.019 --> 00:05:01.379
And we want them to be maintained to a single detector, the detector that the X-ray was incident on.

00:05:01.379 --> 00:05:06.779
That light energy is then converted into an electrical current by the photodiode layer.

00:05:06.779 --> 00:05:12.219
The photosensitive area is going to create or free electrons that are going to then run towards

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:17.420
what's known as the capacitor and ultimately be discharged with the transistor here.

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:23.820
That electrical current for each individual detector is going to be sent towards our computer

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:29.540
for processing via a mechanism known as the application-specific integrated circuit.

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:35.740
And the type of ASIC that we use in conventional CT detectors is what's known as an integration ASIC.

00:05:35.740 --> 00:05:41.940
We take the integral of the curve that we generated when the X-ray photons were incident on this detector.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:48.819
And that integral is the area under the curve, the total amount of X-ray energy that has reached our detector for a period of time.

00:05:48.819 --> 00:05:52.660
So let's look at this head-on. We can see the photodiode layer here.

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:56.819
Only this blue region on the photodiode is sensitive to light.

00:05:56.819 --> 00:06:02.980
The rest of the components here, if X-rays are incident on them or light photons more specifically are incident on them,

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:05.740
they're not going to contribute to our final signal.

00:06:05.740 --> 00:06:11.180
That's what's known as the fill factor, the difference between the area that we actually sensitive to light

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:13.900
versus the total area of the detector.

00:06:13.900 --> 00:06:20.500
The higher the fill factor, the more efficient our detector is because we're able to register more of those light photons.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:26.579
So this photodiode layer has a silicon photosensitive area that's going to receive light.

00:06:26.579 --> 00:06:35.500
It has the capacitor here, which is going to store or accumulate the electrical energy or the electrons that have been freed in this silicon layer over time.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:40.740
We store and store and store until the transistor switch here gets a little bit of current.

00:06:40.780 --> 00:06:46.420
We provide a small amount of current to this transistor switch and that empties the capacitor.

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:51.900
The emptying of the capacitor is giving the total electric charge that we've liberated from the light photons.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:53.939
And that's going to send it towards the ASIC here.

00:06:53.939 --> 00:07:02.300
If we look underneath our detector here, we can see that the circuitry within the detector is linked to the ASIC.

00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:04.900
That's going to send those signals off to our computer.

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:10.220
So let's look at a practical example here where we're going to have incident X-rays hitting our detector.

00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:15.500
An X-ray comes in and it's converted into hundreds or thousands of light photons.

00:07:15.500 --> 00:07:20.860
Those light photons hit the photosensitive area here and a charge is generated.

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:24.260
Light energy is converted into an electrical impulse.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:26.380
That charge is then stored in the capacitor.

00:07:26.380 --> 00:07:30.460
That's the function of a capacitor, to store electrical energy.

00:07:30.460 --> 00:07:36.140
The number of light photons is proportional to the energy of the incident X-ray photon.

00:07:36.139 --> 00:07:41.539
And therefore the stored electrical current that we've sent from the photosensitive area to our capacitor

00:07:41.539 --> 00:07:46.300
is also going to be proportional to the incident X-ray energy.

00:07:46.300 --> 00:07:50.740
Now we set a time interval where we're going to measure all of the X-rays coming in.

00:07:50.740 --> 00:07:58.899
And during that time interval, multiple X-rays are going to hit the detector and send out light photons because of that scintillator layer.

00:07:58.899 --> 00:08:05.500
Those light photons are going to be converted into electrical energy and continually fill up our capacitor here.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:14.620
You can see during this representation here, over time our capacitor is being filled up with stored electrical energy.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:22.259
At a given point in time, that stored electrical energy is going to be released through the ASIC and sent towards our computer.

00:08:22.259 --> 00:08:24.660
Now remember we're looking at just one detector here.

00:08:24.660 --> 00:08:29.980
This detector forms part of a multiple rows of detectors or an array of detectors.

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:35.420
Each one of these detectors is going to be receiving different X-ray energies.

00:08:35.420 --> 00:08:40.940
And we're going to ultimately store different levels of electrical impulses.

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:47.100
When we read out an entire row, you saw that the ASIC actually runs in between each one of these detectors.

00:08:47.100 --> 00:08:51.820
When we flip the transistor switch, we can actually read out an entire row of detectors.

00:08:51.820 --> 00:08:57.259
We're going to get a graph representing the electrical stored energy in the capacitors.

00:08:57.259 --> 00:09:03.259
And that differs depending on the detector location because of the differing anatomy that the X-rays have traveled through.

00:09:03.259 --> 00:09:08.460
We can then convert the stored electrical energy into our sinogram.

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:16.379
We have filled a row of the sinogram based on the incident X-ray photon energy, the number of light photons that were released,

00:09:16.379 --> 00:09:22.779
and then ultimately the amount of electrical charge that that generated on the silicon portion of the photodiode layer.

00:09:22.779 --> 00:09:27.179
That's how conventional computer tomography detectors work.

00:09:27.179 --> 00:09:32.299
Computer tomography detectors, their main characteristics is that there's an indirect conversion.

00:09:32.299 --> 00:09:36.299
The scintillator layer produces light before we create an electrical impulse.

00:09:36.299 --> 00:09:39.739
That's going to differ from photon counting CT detectors.

00:09:39.739 --> 00:09:42.139
And secondly, there's energy integration.

00:09:42.139 --> 00:09:47.819
We're adding up all of the energy and then using that total amount to create our image.

00:09:47.819 --> 00:09:50.620
We're not looking at individual X-ray energies.

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:56.939
Now this leads to a number of shortfalls that photon counting CT detectors are going to try and address.

00:09:56.940 --> 00:10:00.620
The first being that we've got no complex energy discrimination.

00:10:00.620 --> 00:10:08.460
We're not able to accurately say what was the energy of the X-ray photons that were incident on our detector in that period of time.

00:10:08.460 --> 00:10:15.100
We've looked at dual energy CT where we can see two separate X-ray energy levels, but we can't really go much further than that.

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:19.020
Photon counting detectors, because we can look at individual X-ray energies,

00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:24.620
we're going to have much better spectral discrimination and much better tissue discrimination ultimately.

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:27.820
The next problem we have is noise, especially at low doses.

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:31.259
If you cast your mind back to the analogy of the bucket filling with water,

00:10:31.259 --> 00:10:35.019
we're only measuring the total change in the weight of that bucket.

00:10:35.019 --> 00:10:38.860
We aren't measuring individual droplets that are falling into the bucket.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:45.259
So if we say the bucket got a kilogram heavier, how much of that signal was due to just electrical background noise?

00:10:45.259 --> 00:10:48.779
It's hard to differentiate that out because we've just got a total value.

00:10:48.779 --> 00:10:55.179
We'll see in photon counting detectors, we've got a much better primary way to reduce the noise in our image.

00:10:55.179 --> 00:10:58.860
We've looked at noise reduction techniques that apply to conventional CT detectors,

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:06.779
but photon counting CT detectors are going to give us an added level for noise reduction and ultimately improve our signal-to-noise ratio.

00:11:06.779 --> 00:11:10.699
Thirdly, we've got limited spatial resolution in conventional detectors.

00:11:10.699 --> 00:11:13.500
I mentioned the full factor. We've got a lot of dead space here.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:19.899
Our scepter as well are providing place for incident x-rays to hit and provide no meaningful signal.

00:11:19.899 --> 00:11:24.700
The detectors, as we'll see later, are also larger than photon counting detectors.

00:11:24.700 --> 00:11:30.860
We can also have light spreading between adjacent detectors and reducing our spatial resolution.

00:11:30.860 --> 00:11:35.019
And we looked at the factors that influence spatial resolution in the image quality lecture.

00:11:35.019 --> 00:11:40.220
When we look at photon counting CT, you'll see how some of those factors are reduced.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:45.820
We have limited artifact reduction. Again, we can't really tell what energy our photons are coming through.

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:51.500
So an artifact such as beam hardening, where the beam's average energy gets much higher,

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:55.259
we aren't able to accurately detect that in conventional CT detectors.

00:11:55.259 --> 00:12:00.060
And we need to provide post-processing algorithms to, say, reduce the cupping artifact.

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:03.580
We can't address the problem directly at the source.

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:07.980
And lastly, the conventional CT detectors have limited dose efficiency,

00:12:07.980 --> 00:12:10.700
predominantly because of these previous shortfalls.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:13.820
We've got a certain amount of noise that we just have to deal with.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:17.740
We can't improve our signal-to-noise ratio past a specific point.

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:25.660
Much of the dose that passes through the patient is going to reach parts of the detector that don't even contribute to our final image.

00:12:25.660 --> 00:12:31.660
When x-rays are converted to light, we get a loss of energy in that conversion, so that's not a perfectly efficient process.

00:12:31.659 --> 00:12:36.860
Many factors here limit the dose efficiency of CT detectors.

00:12:36.860 --> 00:12:43.819
So let's then have a look at photon-counting CT detectors and compare and contrast that to conventional detectors.

00:12:43.819 --> 00:12:50.299
You'll see here, photon-counting detectors are sandwiched between a cathode layer and an anode layer.

00:12:50.299 --> 00:12:56.459
And there's a large voltage potential that's applied across this detector here in the order of hundreds of volts.

00:12:56.460 --> 00:13:04.139
So we've got a large voltage potential, and sandwiched between these two electrodes is what's known as the semiconductor crystal layer.

00:13:04.139 --> 00:13:10.780
In our examples, we're going to use a crystal layer that's made of cadmium telluride, CDTE, you'll see that used often.

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:17.100
Here's the chemical structure, and cadmium telluride is perfect for this example because it's got good x-ray stopping power.

00:13:17.100 --> 00:13:18.780
It's got a high atomic number.

00:13:18.780 --> 00:13:25.019
It's got lots of valence electrons, which you're going to see becomes important during the generation of signal here.

00:13:25.019 --> 00:13:31.659
It's stable at room temperature, provides the perfect material for this photon-counting CT detector.

00:13:31.659 --> 00:13:36.299
Of note though is that these crystal layers rely on them being perfect.

00:13:36.299 --> 00:13:42.460
If there's any defect in these layers, we're going to get a drastic offset in the accuracy of our signal.

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:44.779
Photon-counting detectors also have an ASIC.

00:13:44.779 --> 00:13:47.659
You can see it running under here and it heads out.

00:13:47.659 --> 00:13:54.059
Now these ASICs are different to the integrated ASIC that we looked at in conventional computed tomography detectors.

00:13:54.059 --> 00:14:00.619
Because those detectors only receive the total amount of energy from a transistor that was releasing stored energy from a capacitor.

00:14:00.619 --> 00:14:03.019
Here there's no capacitor, no transistor.

00:14:03.019 --> 00:14:11.099
These ASICs are measuring an electrical impulse that's created when an incident photon interacts with the semiconductor crystal layer.

00:14:11.099 --> 00:14:18.699
The predominant difference here between conventional CT and photon-counting CT detectors is that this is a direct conversion detector.

00:14:18.699 --> 00:14:22.619
X-ray energy is converted directly into an electrical impulse.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:25.100
There's no light step in the middle.

00:14:25.100 --> 00:14:26.860
There's no scintillator layer here.

00:14:26.860 --> 00:14:28.860
So let's have a look at how that process works.

00:14:28.860 --> 00:14:33.820
We're going to show you how we actually go about measuring signal in photon-counting detectors.

00:14:33.820 --> 00:14:39.259
We have an incident X-ray that is going to interact with the semiconductor layer.

00:14:39.259 --> 00:14:47.899
What happens here is that an electron in that semiconductor layer is going to be released from the valence shell that it's in.

00:14:47.899 --> 00:14:53.819
We think of the outermost electrons in the outermost orbital that's actually filled with electrons as valence electrons.

00:14:53.819 --> 00:14:57.100
They fill an energy band known as the valence band.

00:14:57.100 --> 00:15:05.740
If energy is deposited into that system, those electrons can get enough energy to be released from the valence band and enter what's known as the conduction band.

00:15:05.740 --> 00:15:11.100
Electrons in the conduction band then have the ability to move along an electrical bias.

00:15:11.100 --> 00:15:15.740
And we've created an electrical potential here between the cathode and the anode.

00:15:15.740 --> 00:15:22.220
So as that electron is released from the semiconductor layer, it's going to move towards the anode here.

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:27.419
It's going to move along that electrical field or that electrical potential.

00:15:27.419 --> 00:15:33.820
When the electron is released from the valence band, it leaves what's known as an electron hole.

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:39.019
And the electron and the electron hole together is known as an electron hole pair.

00:15:39.019 --> 00:15:43.500
The electron hole is a potential space, a space where an electron can fill.

00:15:43.500 --> 00:15:50.860
And what we know is that in a specific atom, that electron space will be filled by an adjacent or surrounding electron.

00:15:50.860 --> 00:15:57.820
There's an energy differential that is being created and a surrounding electron is going to fill that hole.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:16:04.539
The process of electrons filling that hole means that the electron hole is going to seemingly move towards the cathode.

00:16:04.539 --> 00:16:07.500
And I'm going to show you exactly how that process works.

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:15.340
The movement of the electron holes towards the cathode and the electrons towards the anode is going to create an electrical pulse.

00:16:15.340 --> 00:16:18.139
And that pulse can be measured by the ASIC.

00:16:18.139 --> 00:16:19.820
Let's look at that process again.

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:27.899
The X-ray hits the semiconductor layer, electron holes travel towards the cathode, and electrons travel towards the anode.

00:16:27.899 --> 00:16:31.980
Let's zoom in on the structure of the semiconductor layer.

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:35.740
You can see this crystal lattice that's been formed in the semiconductor layer.

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:38.379
It's a highly organized, tightly packed structure.

00:16:38.379 --> 00:16:45.500
And I want to give you an extremely basic diagrammatic representation of electrons sitting within this structured crystal layer.

00:16:45.500 --> 00:16:56.060
When an X-ray is incident on this crystal layer, we get, say, the photoelectric effect or Compton scatter that causes an electron to be ejected into the conduction band.

00:16:56.060 --> 00:16:59.100
It's not just one electron, it's a cloud of electrons.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:03.580
We get in the order of tens of thousands of electrons that are being released within this layer.

00:17:03.580 --> 00:17:09.100
That release of the electron results in a cascade of electrons being released, and we call it an electron cloud.

00:17:09.100 --> 00:17:12.700
Notice how that electron cloud is headed towards the anode.

00:17:12.700 --> 00:17:16.059
Now we can see the electron holes in this diagram.

00:17:16.059 --> 00:17:18.059
Which electrons are going to fill these holes?

00:17:18.059 --> 00:17:27.819
Well, because of the potential that we've created across this semiconductor layer, it's these electrons that are going to move towards the anode and fill the hole.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:34.220
As they move towards the anode, look how the electron holes are effectively moving towards the cathode.

00:17:34.220 --> 00:17:38.619
Now the electron holes aren't particles themselves, they're just potential spaces.

00:17:38.619 --> 00:17:44.539
And you see now those electron holes have moved towards the cathode, ultimately creating that electrical pulse.

00:17:44.539 --> 00:17:47.019
Let's look at that more in real time.

00:17:47.019 --> 00:17:50.460
You'll see that the interactions often happen closer to the cathode.

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:53.500
Electron holes move slower than electrons move.

00:17:53.500 --> 00:17:59.420
That's why the cathode is on the patient side of our detector and the anode is on the computer side of our detector.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:01.420
So watch how this happens.

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:08.380
Photoelectric effect or Compton scatter, the hole looks like it's moving towards the cathode and the electrons actually do move towards the anode.

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:09.900
You can watch that again.

00:18:09.900 --> 00:18:14.539
X-ray coming in, electron cloud being released, and holes moving towards the cathode.

00:18:14.539 --> 00:18:18.940
That's the foundation for photon counting CT.

00:18:18.940 --> 00:18:27.580
Now we can have X-rays of different energies reaching our detector and that electron cloud that is released is going to be proportional to those X-ray energies.

00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:33.100
And ultimately the electrical impulse is going to be proportional to the incident X-ray energy.

00:18:33.100 --> 00:18:41.019
And that's how we can not only discern separate X-rays but we can also calculate the energy of those X-rays.

00:18:41.019 --> 00:18:45.259
And that's the major key to photon counting is we've got much more spectral information.

00:18:45.259 --> 00:18:49.819
We've got much better information about the energy of the X-rays that have hit our detector.

00:18:49.819 --> 00:18:56.619
Photon counting detectors not only count X-rays but they bin the X-rays based on the degree of energy that they have.

00:18:56.619 --> 00:19:00.220
We can separate the X-rays into multiple different energy bins.

00:19:00.220 --> 00:19:06.379
High energy, medium energy, low energy bins and actually X-rays maybe that are so low energy that we want to remove from our sample.

00:19:06.379 --> 00:19:13.180
So hopefully you can see that photon counting detectors are going to provide us with much more information than conventional CT detectors.

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:20.539
That's going to lead to a range of benefits and we're going to go through some of those benefits here or advantages of photon counting CT.

00:19:20.539 --> 00:19:28.060
Say X-rays have been incident on a specific detector, just one of our detectors, and we've read out the information with our ASIC here.

00:19:28.060 --> 00:19:36.860
We can see the number of X-ray photons and we can see the incident energy of those X-ray photons based on the area and or each one of these curves.

00:19:36.939 --> 00:19:43.259
The first advantage of photon counting CT, and I've mentioned it, is this intrinsic energy discrimination.

00:19:43.259 --> 00:19:55.259
We looked at dual energy CT. We said that we could have two separate average energy X-ray sources applied to the patient, whether that's alternating X-ray sources or orthogonal X-ray sources.

00:19:55.259 --> 00:20:03.099
And we can see that different tissues respond to different X-ray energies based on their tissue composition.

00:20:03.099 --> 00:20:07.740
Bone is going to respond very differently to a change in X-ray energy, say to liver.

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:16.539
And based on those changes in response or changes in Hounsfield units to different X-ray energies, we could separate out those tissues in post-processing.

00:20:16.539 --> 00:20:23.339
But we only had two X-ray energy sources and they were actually different X-ray spectrums heading towards the patient.

00:20:23.339 --> 00:20:31.579
What we can do in photon counting CT is separate each one of these X-rays into individual energy categories.

00:20:31.579 --> 00:20:40.059
Now we've not only got dual energy sources, we've got multiple energy sources depending on how well we can discriminate the different energy levels.

00:20:40.059 --> 00:20:49.019
And we can use each one of these, we can say we're only going to use the data from X-rays in this energy bin here and see how the tissues respond.

00:20:49.019 --> 00:20:58.539
Now let's see how different the image looks, how different the Hounsfield values are if we use X-rays only in this X-ray bin, this X-ray energy bin.

00:20:58.539 --> 00:21:03.740
And based on those changes in Hounsfield units, we can make assumptions about the tissues within the patient.

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:07.819
And we can much better separate out individual tissues.

00:21:07.819 --> 00:21:21.500
Perhaps we're going to get to a stage where we can really easily separate out tissues with very subtle Hounsfield unit differences based on our ability to have intrinsic energy discrimination in photon counting CT.

00:21:21.500 --> 00:21:25.180
Next we've got a much improved spatial resolution.

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:32.860
You see here in our example, the detector, the anode here is much smaller than our conventional CT detector which is much larger.

00:21:32.860 --> 00:21:36.380
We've got limiting factors with conventional CT detectors.

00:21:36.380 --> 00:21:45.340
One based on the septum, two based on the electrical components that are needed and the fill factor, and three based on how large the photosensitive area is.

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:53.180
We need to have a certain size of photosensitive area to get enough signal that's going to be able to separate signal from noise.

00:21:53.180 --> 00:22:01.820
Because we don't need those septum and we don't need electronics on the top of our anode here, we've got much smaller detector elements.

00:22:01.820 --> 00:22:10.700
And actually reducing the size of the detector elements, reducing the size of each one of those anode pixels, is actually going to be advantageous for photon counting CT.

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:17.740
Because the total number of photons hitting each anode is going to be reduced and we're going to better be able to discriminate out those X-rays.

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:22.860
And you'll see when I talk about some of the challenges we're facing in photon CT, why that becomes important.

00:22:22.859 --> 00:22:26.379
We've also got a much better ability to deal with dose.

00:22:26.379 --> 00:22:32.379
You see, when the X-rays are converted into light, there's an inefficiency there, there's a loss of energy.

00:22:32.379 --> 00:22:38.699
So we're going to need higher exposure to get the same degree of signal as we would in the photon counting CT.

00:22:38.699 --> 00:22:47.819
Again, I've mentioned this now multiple times, there's dead space where X-ray, incident X-ray photons are going to produce light that don't even contribute to our signal.

00:22:47.899 --> 00:22:51.500
We'll see later how noise is much less in photon counting CT.

00:22:51.500 --> 00:22:55.819
We don't need as high a dose and the noise really predominates at lower doses.

00:22:55.819 --> 00:23:00.299
And if we have a good ability to reduce the amount of noise, we can actually use lower doses.

00:23:00.299 --> 00:23:03.579
So there's better dose efficiency in photon counting CT.

00:23:03.579 --> 00:23:06.059
So how then do we go about actually reducing the noise?

00:23:06.059 --> 00:23:09.339
I said an advantage of photon counting CT is noise reduction.

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:14.059
Well, it's a function of this intrinsic energy discrimination.

00:23:14.059 --> 00:23:18.059
We know that noise occurs at high frequencies and at low X-ray energies.

00:23:18.059 --> 00:23:20.539
It gets confused with low X-ray energy photons.

00:23:21.339 --> 00:23:28.139
What we can do is we can apply a threshold and say, you know what, X-ray energy is under a certain point we're not going to use in our image.

00:23:28.139 --> 00:23:31.019
That's going to get rid of the noise within our image.

00:23:31.019 --> 00:23:41.740
We can still manipulate the data that we have here, especially because of the different energy bins, to create an image that has still sharp resolution and high signal, a good signal to noise ratio.

00:23:41.740 --> 00:23:46.859
But we've drastically reduced the amount of noise by not including those lower energy X-ray photons.

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:50.779
Conventional CT just has a total sum of X-rays that hit it.

00:23:50.779 --> 00:23:55.180
It can't take out lower energy photons and include higher energy photons.

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:59.259
That's a major point for noise reduction in photon counting CT.

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:08.220
The electronics here also have less electronic noise as opposed to photon counting CT because each one of our data points are much smaller.

00:24:08.220 --> 00:24:14.299
We're not accumulating a whole load of data and then amplifying that signal as we release it out towards our detector.

00:24:14.299 --> 00:24:20.059
Not only can we reduce noise, but we can actually reduce many artifacts that we get with conventional computer tomography.

00:24:20.779 --> 00:24:31.980
Here what I've tried to represent is a beam hardening artifact where we've got a detector that's getting all of these different X-ray energies, I've just clumped them together, and we've got a predominance of these high X-ray energy photons.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:39.339
And we can know in our algorithm or in our system that our incident X-ray, our average incident X-ray energy is going to be X.

00:24:39.339 --> 00:24:46.059
We've set the kVp, we've set the mas, but the average X-ray photons that are hitting our detector are much harder.

00:24:46.059 --> 00:24:47.980
We can assume that beam hardening has occurred.

00:24:48.860 --> 00:24:59.900
What we can do, because we were able to separate the X-ray energies, discriminate between X-ray energies, is we can remove the higher X-ray energies and we can amplify those lower X-ray energy photons.

00:24:59.900 --> 00:25:03.180
And compensate directly at the source for beam hardening.

00:25:03.180 --> 00:25:14.140
We can say this area had a lot of beam hardening, let's remove those higher X-ray energy photons that are going to cause algorithms to falsely calculate the Hounsfield units as lower values.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:24.300
When we've got those dark regions between two highly attenuating structures like the petrous bones, we've got darker values between them, lower Hounsfield unit values because of that beam hardening.

00:25:24.299 --> 00:25:30.139
We can prevent that from occurring by removing those harder X-rays, those higher energy X-ray photons.

00:25:30.139 --> 00:25:34.220
That's one example of how we can remove artifacts in photon counting CT.

00:25:34.220 --> 00:25:40.220
And because of the sheer volume of data that we're getting, we have potential to address many other artifacts.

00:25:40.220 --> 00:25:43.419
And that brings me to the final advantage in this talk that we're going to talk about.

00:25:43.420 --> 00:25:56.300
Is this enhanced post-processing potential or AI integration big data that we now have the ability to manipulate it more than the data that we had originally received in conventional computer tomography detectors?

00:25:56.300 --> 00:26:04.779
We saw in conventional CT detectors, we filled a sinogram and it was this data that we used to generate the image of one slice.

00:26:04.779 --> 00:26:12.220
Now we're not getting a single reading per detector in each line of the sinogram.

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:15.819
Each detector is outputting multiple different data sets.

00:26:15.819 --> 00:26:21.660
It's outputting how many X-rays are hitting it and it's outputting the energy of each one of those X-rays.

00:26:22.299 --> 00:26:28.700
That extra data, as we've seen with some of these steps, is very powerful in post-processing.

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:34.700
It's very powerful in us saying what's the tissue composition of each voxel within this image that we're creating.

00:26:34.700 --> 00:26:41.980
We've got much more information and as a result, there's a much higher upside to the potential of the data that we're receiving.

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:45.819
So why then doesn't every hospital have a photon counting CT?

00:26:45.819 --> 00:26:50.220
Well firstly, this is a new technology. It was only approved in 2021 by the FDA.

00:26:51.019 --> 00:26:56.220
And obviously, new technology is expensive so that's always going to be a prohibiting factor.

00:26:56.220 --> 00:27:03.900
But there are actually certain challenges that photon counting CT detectors face that we still need to overcome or still need to improve on.

00:27:03.900 --> 00:27:08.460
The first challenge that we face is what's known as pulse pile-up or a count rate limitation.

00:27:09.100 --> 00:27:15.100
If an X-ray photon hits our detector, we get an X-ray pulse and another X-ray photon hits the detector, we get a second pulse.

00:27:15.100 --> 00:27:17.340
And those pulses are proportional to the X-ray energy.

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:22.220
What happens when they hit the detector very similar times or very close to one another?

00:27:22.220 --> 00:27:25.259
The two photons strike the detector almost simultaneously.

00:27:26.140 --> 00:27:28.860
Our output is going to look something like this.

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:33.660
We've got overlapping of those electrical impulses and it's very difficult to separate them out.

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:37.740
We do have algorithms that can try and separate them out, but those algorithms aren't perfect.

00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:40.299
Especially if we've got more than two X-rays hitting the detector.

00:27:41.660 --> 00:27:48.299
There's a limitation into the rate at which we can differentiate between different X-rays hitting the CT detector here.

00:27:48.299 --> 00:27:50.140
This is what's known as pulse pile-up.

00:27:50.140 --> 00:27:56.380
Now pulse pile-up is certainly different to our second challenge which is known as adjacent pixel charge sharing.

00:27:56.940 --> 00:28:06.140
Now we've got one X-ray photon creating a cloud of electrons that head out towards our detector, but they strike two adjacent anodes.

00:28:06.220 --> 00:28:09.259
And those anodes are going to share that electrical signal.

00:28:09.259 --> 00:28:17.180
So instead of the signal that we were expecting for that specific X-ray energy, we've now separated that signal into two adjacent anodes.

00:28:17.820 --> 00:28:22.540
So we are getting a reduction in spatial resolution and we've got an incorrect signal here.

00:28:22.540 --> 00:28:27.980
We're going to say that this X-ray photon was half the X-ray energy that it was truly.

00:28:27.980 --> 00:28:30.220
So we're not truly representing that X-ray energy.

00:28:31.980 --> 00:28:35.100
Our third challenge that we're facing is what's known as detector dead time.

00:28:35.099 --> 00:28:41.500
If an X-ray strikes the detector and then another X-ray is incident on that detector close to that initial interaction,

00:28:42.139 --> 00:28:46.859
we may have a point where that second X-ray is not even registered, it's passed through the detector.

00:28:46.859 --> 00:28:54.459
There's a very small period of time when that detector or that anode is not sensitive to a second pulse and that's what's known as detector dead time.

00:28:56.299 --> 00:29:04.939
In an ideal world, the number of photons that were incident on the X-ray detector and the number of photons that we actually detect would be the same.

00:29:05.579 --> 00:29:10.859
If a hundred photons hit the detector, we would want to register a hundred photons in our computer.

00:29:10.859 --> 00:29:19.339
We want a perfect match-up and that graph would look something like this, a linear graph where the more photons incident would equal the more photons detected.

00:29:19.980 --> 00:29:22.859
In practice, we've got what's known as limited dynamic range.

00:29:23.579 --> 00:29:28.059
At high X-ray flux, at a high number of incident X-ray photons,

00:29:28.059 --> 00:29:34.379
we get a disproportional reduction in the amount of photons that we actually register and send to our computer.

00:29:34.380 --> 00:29:39.260
And that's a function of the dead time and a function of pile-up and count rate limitation.

00:29:40.460 --> 00:29:43.500
What happens here is our graph ends up looking something like this.

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:52.300
When we have high photon rates that arrive too quickly at our detector, we aren't able to process each one of those X-rays individually.

00:29:52.300 --> 00:29:57.020
And not only do we have the dead time or the pulse pile-up, but our ability to process the signal,

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:01.500
process those electrical impulses that are heading towards the ASIC is limited.

00:30:01.500 --> 00:30:05.740
There's a limited bandwidth there. There's a limited sampling frequency that we have there.

00:30:05.740 --> 00:30:09.339
If we exceed that, we get this drop-off in our dynamic range here.

00:30:09.339 --> 00:30:14.220
We don't have the ability to truly represent high areas of X-ray flux.

00:30:14.220 --> 00:30:19.099
And finally, the last challenge that we face is the complexity of this new technology.

00:30:19.099 --> 00:30:23.819
We don't quite know exactly all of the things that we can do with this current technology.

00:30:24.619 --> 00:30:29.099
Cost is always going to be prohibitive and now we're getting so much more data.

00:30:29.099 --> 00:30:33.259
And that data is going to require much more advanced signal processing.

00:30:33.259 --> 00:30:37.419
That individual detector is not giving us one readout value per projection,

00:30:37.419 --> 00:30:39.500
like in conventional computer tomography.

00:30:39.500 --> 00:30:42.859
It's giving us multiple readouts for each and every projection.

00:30:42.859 --> 00:30:47.500
It's not just a doubling of the amount of data, it's an exponential increase in the amount of data.

00:30:48.059 --> 00:30:52.459
Manufacturing these components are also much more expensive currently and the hospitals need to

00:30:52.459 --> 00:30:57.259
justify the cost, whether it's beneficial to the hospital or whether it's beneficial to the patient.

00:30:57.259 --> 00:31:00.779
And because this is a new technology, there aren't that many providers here.

00:31:00.779 --> 00:31:03.660
We need competition to drive down the cost.

00:31:03.660 --> 00:31:06.859
And I've included this graph here. This is what's known as Moore's law.

00:31:06.859 --> 00:31:11.420
And Moore predicted that in the 70s that the number of transistors that are used in a chip

00:31:11.420 --> 00:31:16.460
is going to double every two years. And that's pretty much what has happened over the last 50

00:31:16.460 --> 00:31:22.700
years. That the chip size has gotten smaller and the number of chips and our processing power has

00:31:22.700 --> 00:31:28.140
gotten exponentially bigger. This is an exponential scale on the y-axis of our graph.

00:31:29.340 --> 00:31:34.539
Whilst all of the requirement is increasing, we get this drastic reduction in the cost

00:31:34.539 --> 00:31:39.740
to manufacture these components. And we can assume in CT or any technology that we're using

00:31:39.740 --> 00:31:45.420
in radiology, as our demands increase and as technology gets better, we're going to drive

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:49.660
down cost. And these kind of technologies are going to become more and more affordable.

00:31:49.660 --> 00:31:54.940
And hopefully the applications that we can use Photon Counting CT is only going to increase.

00:31:55.500 --> 00:31:59.660
And as I said, this has the potential to be a stepwise increase in the technology,

00:31:59.660 --> 00:32:03.500
from conventional computer tomography to photon counting computer tomography.

00:32:04.220 --> 00:32:09.660
So I hope that's made sense. This is just a broad bird's eye view introduction to Photon Counting CT.

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:15.340
As the technology develops, I'm sure we're going to get an expansion of the underlying physics

00:32:15.339 --> 00:32:20.699
that contribute to this technology. So that brings us to the end of this learning pathway.

00:32:20.699 --> 00:32:25.819
I really have enjoyed sharing this information with you and I hope the information has been

00:32:25.819 --> 00:32:30.699
helpful to you. If you've enjoyed this course, please be sure to let me know. I've linked a

00:32:30.699 --> 00:32:34.939
question bank below if you want to now test your knowledge in an exam setting, where I've taken

00:32:34.939 --> 00:32:40.220
actual past paper exam questions and I answer those questions in video format, showing you why

00:32:40.220 --> 00:32:44.619
I've asked the question that way, how the question could be asked differently, why the other options

00:32:44.619 --> 00:32:48.139
to the questions are wrong. It's a really valuable resource if you're studying for a

00:32:48.139 --> 00:32:52.699
specific physics exam. Until next time, I'll see you all. Goodbye everybody.

